images.title: Visitor Center on the Prairie
images.altText: The visitor center sits in the middle of mixed grass prairie.
images.caption: From the Fossil Hills Trail the Visitor Center is a ship in a sea of prairie grasses.

images.title: The Agate Fossil Hills and Tipis
images.altText: Tipis and Fossil Hills represent the two subjects that Agate Fossil Beds interprets.
images.caption: One of the first impressions that visitors have are the tipis and the Fossil Hills.

images.title: A July Storm Passes
images.altText: Thunderheads are common in July.
images.caption: Summer storms include thunderheads and lightning and can be exciting and dangerous.

images.title: Dinohyus in the Visitor Center Fossil Diorama
images.altText: The Dinohyus was a scavenger, nicknamed "Terrible Pig"
images.caption: Visitors stare in wonder at the huge head of the "apex" predator of the plains some 20 million years ago.

images.title: The James H. Cook collection
images.altText: This buckskin shirt decorated with quills was worn by Red Cloud.
images.caption: Visitors agree that this shirt decorated with quillwork and worn by Red Cloud of the Oglala Lakota is a priceless piece of history.

images.title: Great Temple and Lesser Temple Mound
images.altText: mounds
images.caption: The Great Temple Mound is the largest mound at the park, it stands at 55 feet tall.

images.title: Earth Lodge
images.altText: earth lodge
images.caption: The Earth Lodge was used as a council chamber for the Mississippian Culture (900-1600)

images.title: Earth Lodge Floor
images.altText: earth lodge floor
images.caption: The earth Lodge floor is original it was carbon dated to 1015.

images.title: The Funeral Mound
images.altText: funeral mound
images.caption: The Funeral Mound was by prehistoric cultures to bury their dead. Today there are still remains instead the mound

images.title: Clovis Point
images.altText: spear point
images.caption: This Clovis point is the first spear found east of the Mississippi River. It was carbon dated to 10,000 BC

images.title: Cimarron National Grassland
images.altText: Warm light from the setting sun gives an orange glow to a rock bluff overlooking a grassland.
images.caption: Visit Cimarron National Grassland to experience the Santa Fe Trail.

images.title: Neosho River Crossing, Council Grove
images.altText: A wide river with green grass parks on the side.
images.caption: The Neosho River in Council Grove was an important crossing on the trail.

images.title: Bent's Old Fort National Historic Site, La Junta, Colorado
images.altText: emigrant wagons pulled by oxen and horses cross the prairie with people walking alongside
images.caption: After spending weeks crossing hundreds of miles of lonely and desolate prairie, a trading post appeared: a welcome respite where travelers could repair their wagon and trade for coffee, sugar, blankets, and ammunition.

images.title: Wagon Mound, Mora County, New Mexico
images.altText: desert landscape with a mountain that looks like a wagon from a distance, verdant green grasses
images.caption: Wagon Mound was a landmark on the Santa Fe Trail. Coming from Raton, New Mexico, travelers looked for this wagon-like hill to know that they were close to Santa Fe. Leave Interstate 25 at the village of Wagon Mound in Mora County to find this landmark.

images.title: Fort Union, New Mexico
images.altText: A stone path leads into the distance next to adobe ruins.
images.caption: The Santa Fe Trail traverses through Fort Union.

images.title: Clubhouse Overlook
images.altText: Sunset picture with high vantage point overlooking river with fall colors and sun setting in distanc
images.caption: Ozark National Scenic Riverways has some spectacular scenery.

images.title: Big Spring
images.altText: A sunrise photo with blue turbulent water and a algae colored rock with trees overhanging
images.caption: Big Spring produces more than 250 million gallons of water per day.

images.title: Rocky Falls
images.altText: a brown gravel bar with distant waterfall of water flowing down over brown rocks
images.caption: Rocky Falls is a popular picnic area and swimming hole located near the center of Ozark National Scenic Riverways.

images.title: Prairie Hollow Gorge
images.altText: looking down through large brown/grey/purple boulders with creek in middle and forest in distance
images.caption: Prairie Hollow Gorge is located near the Two Rivers junction, off State Route V.

images.title: Current River near Pulltite
images.altText: A red canoe on gravel bar with clear blue stream behind and green forest
images.caption: The clear water of the Current River is perfect for floating.

images.title: Klepzig Mill

images.caption: Klepzig Mill is a little off the beaten path but worth the trip.

images.title: Alley Mill-Winter

images.caption: Alley Mill is a popular destination.

images.title: Klepzig Mill-Shut In

images.caption: Klepzig Mill has a series of shut-ins along the creek
